==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mire
<hw>Mire</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mire</ets>, <ets>myre</ets>;
akin to Icel. <ets>m<?/rr</ets> swamp, Sw. <ets>myra</ets> marshy
ground, and perh. to E. <ets>moss</ets>.]</ety> <def>Deep mud; wet,
spongy earth.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He his rider from the lofty steed⟦br⟧
Would have cast down and trod in dirty <qex>mire</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mire crow</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the pewit, or
laughing gull.</cd> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Mire
drum</b></col>, <cd>the European bittern.</cd> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mire
<hw>Mire</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mired</conjf> <pr>(m⟦imac⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Miring</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause or permit to stick fast in mire; to plunge
or fix in mud; <as>as, to <ex>mire</ex> a horse or wagon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To stick or entangle; to
involve in difficulties; -- often used in the passive or predicate form;
<as>as, we got <ex>mired</ex> in bureaucratic red tape and it took years
longer than planned</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To soil with mud or foul matter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Smirched thus and <qex>mired</qex> with infamy.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mire</ent>⟦br⟧

